<body>
<p t="3840" d="6240">Madrid, the center of Spain—geographically, 
politically, culturally. This week, we want  </p>
<p t="10080" d="5600">to learn about what it really means to be a 
Madrileño. We want to experience the palaces, the  </p>
<p t="15680" d="6960">plazas, the football, the jamón. This is eating 
good. This is sitting good. Thank you, Madrid.</p>
<p t="22640" d="4960">But Madrid is not a new place for me. The 
last time I came here, it was 2007 on a family  </p>
<p t="27600" d="6880">vacation. My hair was bigger, and my suitcase was 
half Abercrombie polos. And I have never been to  </p>
<p t="34480" d="4800">a Spanish-speaking country outside of my home 
country of Mexico, and this place surprised me  </p>
<p t="39280" d="5440">in the way it felt like home but also slightly 
different in the weirdest ways—the different  </p>
<p t="44720" d="5040">words they use, like “botros,” the food, 
and how delicious it all was. I was hooked.</p>
<p t="49760" d="6320">Now I&#39;m back years later and I&#39;ve got a big 
question on my mind. Has Madrid changed?</p>
<p t="59840" d="5120">Good morning, travelers. We made it to 
Spain. You guys have been asking for this  </p>
<p t="64960" d="5120">series for I don&#39;t even know how long. 
I know it&#39;s early. Madrid is waking up,  </p>
<p t="70080" d="4960">and we&#39;re also waking up, and we&#39;re going to 
start this journey over here in Plaza del Sol.</p>
<p t="75040" d="5360">This is supposed to be a 72-hour guide to Madrid. 
But yesterday we had some flight complications,  </p>
<p t="80400" d="4880">and now we have to do everything we 
want to see here in 48 hours. So,  </p>
<p t="85280" d="4800">hi, Plaza—and bye, Plaza—because I 
have some churros I&#39;m desperately  </p>
<p t="90080" d="3760">wanting to eat right now. Let&#39;s 
go get some Madrid breakfast.</p>
<p t="106720" d="10000">Okay. Any day that we can start with 
churros is going to be a good day.  </p>
<p t="116720" d="2880">This has been the meal I&#39;ve been most excited for  </p>
<p t="119600" d="5200">in our nine-part series here in Europe. 
The smell in this place is incredible.</p>
<p t="124800" d="5920">A lot of people come to Madrid and they do churros 
and chocolate elsewhere at a very popular place,  </p>
<p t="130720" d="5440">but this place is super underrated. 
It&#39;s been family-owned for generations.  </p>
<p t="136160" d="3360">This chocolate looks like they&#39;ve just taken a  </p>
<p t="139520" d="4400">chocolate bar and melted it and served 
it to me. I&#39;m so excited to try this.</p>
<p t="143920" d="3200">And according to Martín, you can dip them.</p>
<p t="147840" d="2320">No—you must. You must dip them.</p>
<p t="150160" d="6560">I&#39;ve never done that with a 
churro, so I&#39;m very excited. Whoa,  </p>
<p t="156720" d="11840">that is some thick chocolate. Holy Toledo. This 
is amazing. Do we have breakfast plans tomorrow?</p>
<p t="168560" d="720">We do.</p>
<p t="169280" d="3520">Ah, dang it. I want to come back 
here. Maybe before we leave,  </p>
<p t="172800" d="2480">before we go on the plane. It&#39;s so good.</p>
<p t="175280" d="5600">We needed to order more, guys, because 
that&#39;s too little for great chocolate.  </p>
<p t="180880" d="3920">And we ordered these ones. These ones, they 
don&#39;t call it churros. They call it “porras.”</p>
<p t="184800" d="3360">It&#39;s fine to me. It&#39;s like a “churrote.”</p>
<p t="196240" d="2000">Which ones are better?</p>
<p t="198240" d="4160">Really? Dang it, I ate almost that whole plate.</p>
<p t="202400" d="2960">These ones, because I think the 
chocolate tastes more over there,  </p>
<p t="205360" d="3040">and it&#39;s less crunchy, but 
it&#39;s good for the chocolate.</p>
<p t="208400" d="1120">Oh, interesting.</p>
<p t="209520" d="6800">It&#39;s safe to say that Churrería Chocolatería 1902 
is definitely underrated. But our next stop—well,  </p>
<p t="216320" d="3920">no one&#39;s missing it. This is where Madrid 
puts its biggest moments on display.</p>
<p t="220240" d="2720">This one, this plaza right 
now, it&#39;s called Plaza Mayor,  </p>
<p t="222960" d="4640">but it has been called different 
names—Plaza de la Real, Plaza Real,  </p>
<p t="227600" d="5200">Plaza de la Constitución, Plaza de 
la República. So many, many names.</p>
<p t="232800" d="4000">So this is nice because normally there&#39;s a lot of 
people sitting over here so you cannot see this,  </p>
<p t="236800" d="6160">but it tells you the story about this place. 
It used to be bullfighting over here. Also,  </p>
<p t="242960" d="4080">they tell you the story about the 
different fires in this plaza.  </p>
<p t="247040" d="9520">This one, for instance, is in 1790. The name 
of the architect. And there were also trials  </p>
<p t="256560" d="5840">over here—but also carnivals. So it&#39;s a very 
important plaza for the history of Madrid.</p>
<p t="262400" d="3760">It&#39;s very good that we have to see this 
before it&#39;s completely full of people.</p>
<p t="266160" d="4800">There is something I was always curious about 
in Madrid. I heard rumors about cookies made  </p>
<p t="270960" d="5760">from nuns in a 17th-century monastery 
called Monasterio del Corpus Christi. So,  </p>
<p t="276720" d="4800">of course, we had to find out if it was real.</p>
<p t="281520" d="3200">Where are you taking us?</p>
<p t="284720" d="1280">Get some candies.</p>
<p t="286000" d="5120">Juliana had questions—fair ones—because 
yeah, there&#39;s no one else over here.  </p>
<p t="291120" d="4880">And telling her I saw on the internet we 
can buy sweets in this completely empty  </p>
<p t="296000" d="6240">monastery does sound like a good plot for a 
horror movie. But you need to trust me here.</p>
<p t="302240" d="2960">This is so strange.</p>
<p t="308160" d="3760">What? You can buy this here in this church?</p>
<p t="311920" d="640">Definitely.</p>
<p t="312560" d="3600">There&#39;s no one working here.</p>
<p t="325200" d="4400">Today, we&#39;ll be buying the cookies without 
being face to face with anyone. Instead,  </p>
<p t="329600" d="4880">we&#39;ll use this wooden turnstile to buy 
what they call “galletas de convento.”</p>
<p t="337680" d="5120">That has to be the craziest way I&#39;ve 
ever bought cookies in my life. Martín,  </p>
<p t="342800" d="3200">and look at that—we got the 
whole box to take home with us.</p>
<p t="346000" d="2320">What kind did we even get? I 
was so swept up in the moment.</p>
<p t="348320" d="720">It&#39;s almond.</p>
<p t="349040" d="3440">Oh my gosh, that&#39;s going to be so 
good. We&#39;re going to try these,  </p>
<p t="352480" d="4400">but the thing is we&#39;re cramming three 
days’ worth of eating into two. So,  </p>
<p t="356880" d="2080">I think we&#39;re just going to 
take it home as a souvenir.</p>
<p t="358960" d="720">Definitely.</p>
<p t="359680" d="1840">But that was a great experience.</p>
<p t="361520" d="1280">Yeah, super cool.</p>
<p t="362800" d="5200">Across town is our next spot, so we hop the 
metro and head to Parque del Retiro. Once a  </p>
<p t="368000" d="3520">royal playground for King Philip IV, 
now it&#39;s one of the few places where  </p>
<p t="371520" d="6800">Madrid actually slows down. There are 15,000 
trees, 350 acres, and these cute little boats  </p>
<p t="378320" d="8800">and ducks that made us forget for a minute 
that we&#39;re in the middle of a capital city.</p>
<p t="404080" d="4000">We weren&#39;t supposed to be here. But guess 
what? When you have a fire under your butt  </p>
<p t="408080" d="4800">to get things moving, sometimes you end up 
doing things faster than you expected. So,  </p>
<p t="412880" d="3120">we had a little spot because 
we can&#39;t keep eating food.  </p>
<p t="416000" d="4320">We&#39;re still full from the churros, and we&#39;re 
very glad we&#39;re here because it looks amazing.</p>
<p t="420320" d="6480">Even though I think the biggest attraction of 
this park—that is, the Crystal Palace—is closed,  </p>
<p t="426800" d="4000">still, it’s a beautiful place to be. 
The symmetry, the people on their little  </p>
<p t="430800" d="5520">boats and the ducks and the little pond 
over here, the school kids walking by.</p>
<p t="436320" d="2720">Yeah, people walking their dogs. It&#39;s a beautiful,  </p>
<p t="439040" d="5840">beautiful morning. And I&#39;m very grateful 
I&#39;m alive to see this beautiful park.</p>
<p t="444880" d="1440">That was really sweet, honey.</p>
<p t="446320" d="4800">It&#39;s a nice time to be alive over 
here in Madrid in a morning like this.</p>
<p t="451120" d="4400">It is. I agree.
Okay, enough being sentimental. We&#39;re hungry  </p>
<p t="455520" d="6000">again. And when lunchtime hits in Madrid, there&#39;s 
only one place you gotta go—Mercado San Miguel.</p>
<p t="461520" d="5280">This place has been around for over a century, 
but it wasn&#39;t like this last time I was here.  </p>
<p t="466800" d="5840">For a while, it was falling apart and was almost 
demolished entirely. But in 2009, it came back  </p>
<p t="472640" d="5440">to life, and now it&#39;s one of the best examples 
of Madrid&#39;s revival—and a good place to eat.</p>
<p t="478080" d="2320">Oh my god, that looks like 
something I want. Oh my god,  </p>
<p t="480400" d="5040">it smells so good in here. And we&#39;re hungry, 
so that&#39;s the perfect combination. Oh my gosh,  </p>
<p t="485440" d="5600">we&#39;re like five feet in and we already have 
three places on our “definitely want that” list.</p>
<p t="491040" d="2400">I know. Probably we&#39;re going to find more.</p>
<p t="498720" d="3760">We get a lot of things here, like 
this sampler of various tortillas  </p>
<p t="502480" d="4480">from a stand called Picolisto, and this 
monster of a tapa at Mozzarella Bar.</p>
<p t="506960" d="6720">This place is the epitome of girl dinner—and 
I love it. Lots of just little things to snack  </p>
<p t="513680" d="7760">on. But I am eyeing this bad boy. Look at 
all this burrata cheese. When I saw this,  </p>
<p t="521440" d="4720">I knew immediately I was going to inhale this 
in about 15 seconds flat. It looks so good.</p>
<p t="526160" d="5200">It&#39;s my favorite. This one, it&#39;s called the 
Martín because it has—it&#39;s not called like that,  </p>
<p t="531360" d="5600">but I name it like that because it has everything 
that Martín likes. Olive, dried tomato, cheese,  </p>
<p t="536960" d="3920">pickle. Come on. I&#39;m going to start doing 
this whenever I’m watching football at home.</p>
<p t="540880" d="5920">Yeah. Honestly, I don&#39;t even know how to 
eat this. Oh, it&#39;s going to fall. Okay.</p>
<p t="546800" d="5760">Oh my god. There&#39;s like this sweet 
tomato jam on top and so much burrata.  </p>
<p t="552560" d="5360">They know me. This is like an entire 
burrata portion in one bite. So good.</p>
<p t="557920" d="4720">I&#39;m going to try this. And for a Mexican 
like myself, I have to tell you the tortilla  </p>
<p t="562640" d="7360">here is very different because it&#39;s made of 
potato and eggs—not like the one at home. The  </p>
<p t="570000" d="5040">bread is toasted, and then the tortilla 
patata is not well done, which I like.</p>
<p t="575040" d="4400">And you don&#39;t mean not well done like bad—you 
mean not like super completely cooked.</p>
<p t="579440" d="3600">Exactly. That&#39;s the way it has to be. And 
also on top, it was like a little sauce.  </p>
<p t="583040" d="4400">I thought it was tomato, but no—it 
was a little spicy, which I love.</p>
<p t="587440" d="4400">Now, don&#39;t tell the other countries or 
the other cities, but for me personally,  </p>
<p t="591840" d="4560">Madrid is in the top five cities in the 
entire world where you eat the best.</p>
<p t="596400" d="2480">It&#39;s amazing. It&#39;s amazing. It&#39;s 
amazing. You know what I&#39;m saying?</p>
<p t="598880" d="2480">And I&#39;m enjoying. I&#39;m in heaven right now.</p>
<p t="601360" d="2720">Now, one of the biggest things we 
were warned about before coming to  </p>
<p t="604080" d="4560">Spain was pickpocketing—especially in 
Madrid and Barcelona. Every local we  </p>
<p t="608640" d="4080">met had a story. And once you&#39;ve been in 
a crowded market like this, you get it.</p>
<p t="612720" d="4800">So, some tips we always tell our viewers: keep 
your phone in zip pockets, use crossbody bags  </p>
<p t="617520" d="4800">and keep them on you at all times, and turn 
your backpacks to the front in busy areas.</p>
<p t="622320" d="4320">But here&#39;s something nobody talks 
about—digital pickpocketing.</p>
<p t="626640" d="4480">Today&#39;s video is brought to you by NordVPN, 
who keeps us safe online while we travel.  </p>
<p t="631120" d="3680">Because just like someone can reach into your 
pocket in real life, someone can reach into  </p>
<p t="634800" d="5600">your device on an open network and grab your 
passwords, banking details, even your location.</p>
<p t="640400" d="2160">We&#39;ve been guilty of clicking any free Wi-Fi  </p>
<p t="642560" d="3440">we find. But sometimes that 
Wi-Fi is a little too free.</p>
<p t="646000" d="4640">But it’s not just cafes. Even hotel 
Wi-Fi or airport networks can be risky,  </p>
<p t="650640" d="4400">especially whenever you&#39;re booking flights 
or checking your bank account. That data  </p>
<p t="655040" d="4080">is just floating around for anybody 
to grab it if you&#39;re not protected.</p>
<p t="659120" d="3520">That&#39;s why we never log into public 
Wi-Fi anymore without a VPN. We use  </p>
<p t="662640" d="4480">NordVPN because it keeps everything 
encrypted, even if the Wi-Fi isn&#39;t.</p>
<p t="667120" d="2480">And it&#39;s not just about safety. When we&#39;re abroad,  </p>
<p t="669600" d="4560">websites sometimes block access just because 
we&#39;re not in our home country—like airline sites  </p>
<p t="674160" d="4640">showing different prices or even our favorite 
streaming networks not working. With NordVPN,  </p>
<p t="678800" d="3040">we can switch our location and use 
the internet like we&#39;re back home.</p>
<p t="681840" d="4640">So yeah, if you&#39;re traveling, work remote, 
stream content, or you want peace of mind  </p>
<p t="686480" d="6800">when you hop online, NordVPN is what you need. 
Go to nordvpn.com/local for a 2-year plan plus  </p>
<p t="693280" d="5040">four extra months at a huge discount, 
